\begin{IDEAS}
1. **Title: Information-Theoretic Entropy of Neutrino Mass Hierarchies**
Objective: Quantify the Information Gain (Kullback-Leibler divergence) between the prior and posterior distributions of the neutrino mass sum under the NH and IH models. This study determines which hierarchy is more "constrained" by current DESI DR2 data, providing a measure of how much cosmological data reduces our uncertainty regarding the mass ordering beyond simple Bayes factors.

2. **Title: Sensitivity of Bayesian Model Selection to Dark Energy Parameterization**
Objective: Investigate how the inclusion of dynamical dark energy (w0waCDM) versus standard ΛCDM shifts the Bayes factor for the neutrino mass hierarchy. By analyzing the shift in the posterior volume for Σmν, this work assesses whether the preference for NH is robust against potential degeneracies between neutrino mass and time-varying dark energy.

3. **Title: The Impact of CMB Likelihood Selection on Neutrino Hierarchy Evidence**
Objective: Perform a comparative analysis of Bayes factors derived from distinct CMB pipelines (CamSpec, plik, and L-H) combined with DESI DR2 BAO measurements. This research identifies how systematic differences in high-multipole CMB likelihoods influence the evidence for NH, evaluating the stability of the hierarchy preference across different cosmological data subsets.

4. **Title: Geometric Prior Volumes and the Jeffreys-Fisher Scale in Neutrino Physics**
Objective: Explore the mathematical geometry of the HS prior (Jeffreys-Fisher) by mapping the Fisher information matrix of the PMNS-oscillation parameters onto the mass space. This study provides a rigorous foundation for why specific prior choices lead to different evidence outcomes, formalizing the relationship between oscillation-space constraints and the resulting mass-space volume.

5. **Title: Forecasting the "Decisive" Threshold for Neutrino Mass Hierarchy**
Objective: Model the hypothetical evolution of the Bayes factor K as a function of future survey precision, assuming a true NH state. By extrapolating current DESI DR2 constraints, this research defines the exact threshold of cosmological sensitivity required to reach the "decisive" (K > 100) evidence level, providing a roadmap for next-generation spectroscopic surveys.

6. **Title: Majorana Neutrino Mass Posteriors and the Detection Reach of 0νββ**
Objective: Map the DESI DR2-constrained neutrino mass posteriors to the effective Majorana neutrino mass (mββ) parameter space. This study identifies the overlap between the current cosmological preference for NH and the sensitivity reach of upcoming neutrinoless double-beta decay experiments, explicitly quantifying the probability of signal detection given the NH hierarchy.

7. **Title: Consistency Checks: Comparing Feldman-Cousins and Bayesian Evidence**
Objective: Contrast the frequentist confidence intervals (Feldman-Cousins) with Bayesian evidence ratios when applied to the non-negative physical boundary of neutrino mass. This research highlights the philosophical and practical discrepancy between "exclusion limits" and "model selection," offering a unified view of how these frameworks treat the zero-mass lower bound.

8. **Title: Marginalization Over Systematic Uncertainties in Neutrino Mass Constraints**
Objective: Assess the robustness of the NH evidence by incorporating nuisance parameters from the DESI DR2 chains (e.g., galaxy bias, growth rate) directly into the Bayesian evidence integral. This objective determines if the preference for NH is an artifact of the central cosmological model or if it holds under broader, more conservative parameter marginalization.

9. **Title: Global Oscillation Data Tensions and Their Influence on Hierarchy Evidence**
Objective: Evaluate the impact of the Δχ² tension in global oscillation fits (with vs. without Super-Kamiokande atmospheric data) on the final Bayes factor. This study quantifies how sensitive the "evidence" for NH is to variations in the underlying laboratory-based neutrino oscillation measurements, isolating the contribution of particle physics data versus cosmological data.

10. **Title: The Hierarchical Logarithmic Prior: A Bayesian Sensitivity Analysis**
Objective: Test the stability of the SJPV (hierarchical log-normal) framework by varying hyperprior boundaries for the mass generation scale. By analyzing the sensitivity of the Bayes factor to these hyperparameters, this research establishes the degree of "prior-dependence" in the current evidence for the normal mass hierarchy.
\end{IDEAS}


