**Description**: This research quantifies the statistical preference for the Normal Hierarchy (NH) by applying the Jimenez et al. (2022) Bayesian framework to the latest DESI DR2 cosmological constraints (Σmν < 0.0642 eV at 95% CL). To ensure physical rigor, we replace the Gaussian approximation with non-parametric Kernel Density Estimation (KDE) of the DESI MCMC chains, capturing the non-Gaussian posterior behavior near the physical boundary of Σmν ≥ 0. We compute Bayes factors (K) using both the hierarchical logarithmic (SJPV) and objective Jeffreys-Fisher (HS) priors, incorporating updated NuFIT 6.0 oscillation parameters to resolve the shifting Δχ² between orderings. The study explicitly marginalizes over Majorana CP-violating phases when deriving the effective mass mββ, ensuring the double-beta decay projections are robust against phase-space uncertainties. We systematically analyze the sensitivity of the evidence to dark energy extensions by contrasting ΛCDM and w0waCDM (Σmν < 0.163 eV) chains. Finally, we provide a historical reconstruction of the Bayes factor evolution from 2002 to 2025, demonstrating how the current DESI DR2 data elevates the preference for NH to the "decisive" regime on the Jeffreys scale.


Iteration 1:
Idea: **Title**: Decisive Bayesian Evidence for the Normal Neutrino Mass Hierarchy from DESI DR2

**Description**: This study quantifies the statistical preference for the Normal Hierarchy (NH) by applying the Jimenez et al. (2022) Bayesian framework to the DESI DR2 cosmological constraints (Σmν < 0.0642 eV). To ensure physical consistency at the boundary of Σmν ≥ 0, we employ reflected kernel density estimation (KDE) on the fully marginalized DESI DR2 chains to prevent unphysical probability leakage. We compute Bayes factors (K) using both SJPV hierarchical logarithmic and HS (Jacobian-based) priors, explicitly quantifying the systematic variance in K as a function of prior volume to substantiate the evidence strength. The analysis incorporates updated NuFIT 6.0 oscillation parameters and treats historical cosmological limits within the same Bayesian architecture to provide a consistent temporal reconstruction of the evidence, avoiding frequentist-Bayesian comparison fallacies. Projections for the effective Majorana mass mββ are derived under the explicit theoretical assumption of vanishing Majorana CP-violating phases, providing a robust, data-driven comparison against the sensitivity of next-generation 0νββ experiments. Finally, we evaluate the robustness of the hierarchy preference by testing the sensitivity of the Bayes factor to dark energy model variations (ΛCDM vs. w0waCDM).

